//Loot: Agent Malignant energy courses through this outlandish piece of wood. Pried from the corpse of a dead dragon, the scale continues to radiate heat. They are wrapped tightly in chains to keep them still. The dragon's wrath persists even in death. Prized by alchemists and wizards. Feared by the superstitious. It is kept in a sack, but that doesn't reassure others that they aren't being watched. Translucent and light enough to float for extended periods of time. Wherever they fall, nature will flourish. It warps anything it comes into contact with. Light and air bend around it. No one will touch them with their bare hands. A delicacy in some taverns. Some soldiers can't keep themselves from partaking in the tinctures that can be brewed from it. Nearly every part of a Strangleweed is mortally toxic. This is the one part that isn't. A favorite tool of Assassins and entrepreneuring Rogues. Poison is always in demand. Softer than regular silk, but as resilient as steel. Commonly used to fashion clothes for Nobles and Royalty. Easily mistaken for a jagged rock, they curl up with finality at the moment of death. Mundane and with many practical uses. Merchants never seem to have enough of them. Wizards horde these objects ravenously, if only to keep them out of the hands of their detractors. A coveted component for the assembly of Golems, as Sight Enchantments are unable to rival the sensory properties of these objects. Adequate in the creation of protective clothing. Rumors have it that the inhuman strength and mentality of the Warriors of Discord are the results of frequently imbibing such liquids. A curiosity at best. A grim fate at worst. It is not unheard of for a kingdom to vanish under a tide of Lycanthropic vermin. Fanciful as a decoration in one's cap, or practical as a particularly grand writing utensil. Cultists favor them for practicing falconry with their bare arms. With particularly giant falcons. There is virtually nothing that can't be grown abundantly within such imbued earth. Noblemen favor them in the creation of their coveted Estates. Determining the use of its corrosive properties is best left up to the alchemists making the purchase. One can only hope it is not the result of a Rogue's indiscriminate graverobbing. Remains too pulverized to be put to rest are instead put to other uses. Trolls have no brains or spines, only coils upon coils of this chaotic mass. Safe enough, despite their potential. The sproes seem to be incapable of germinating outside of whatever realm they originate from. Highly concentrated necromantic magic is infused in what little remains of this monstrous Undead. Merely holding it infuses brief bouts of bloodlust. Only specialized practitioners could make use of such a trophy. Favored in the Northern provinces for their supernatural resilience to declining temperatures. Pristinely white with streaks of blood running over it. It could almost be mistaken for an Ivory Dagger. In certain cases of prolonged Lycanthropy, the victim will not return to their natural form upon death. A ghastly facsimile of a human hand, the tips and even the joints are jaggedly sharp and ludicrously elongated. Only a piece of the grisly and painful transformation. Only the telltale quivering and twitching give away that this piece of flesh still pulses with necromantic reanimation.
Some primitive communities use these as currency. Its only real worth is proving that somewhere, at some time, a Goblin died.
